{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"97283b92-dcd0-4a22-afec-fd6b536ec342","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- Makes it installable via: dotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — this is the critical property that makes `dotnet pack` produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (defaults to the assembly name if omitted).\n3. **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — tools must be console apps.\n\n### Publishing workflow\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nNo other special configuration is needed for stdio-based MCP servers — they just read stdin/write stdout, which works naturally as a dotnet tool.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8af43a35-7077-4b27-9275-3d973b994417","outputTokens":501,"requestId":"AC16:32F0B0:B2991B:DECE2F:6A012E09"},"id":"cc012ef9-fc0f-4a0a-90d3-e9db6956a867","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:17:07.611Z","parentId":"a485c3d5-41fe-45ec-8084-359386baeabb"}
